V. Bellum scripturus sum, quod populus Romanus¹ c'um J ugurtha, Rege Numidarum, gessit: primum, quia

Hanc ego non, ut me defendere tentet, adoro. Non est confessi culpa tuenda rei. Liv. book 6, c. 12, Romanus dictator castris eo die positis, postero cum auspicato prodisset, hostiaque caesa pacem Defim adorasset. Nimirum adorare, says Broukhusius, place cited, proprie erat, manum ad os admotam osculari3 qni quia precantium ac supplicantium cultus erat, ideo positum fuit pro orare. See the learned Muretus, in his Var. Lection. lib. 17, c. 14, who shows that Remigrare is used by Plautus for miyrare, reddere for dare. Sic (continues he) redire dicitur haere- ditas, quae tum primum defertur. Terentius, Ea ad hos redibat lege haereditas. Cato de re rustica. Nunc ad rem redeam, quod promisi, institutum principium hoc erit. And then he quotes the sentence above, Nunc ad inceptum redeo, and reads institutum, et non inceptum. Recepit is for cepit in Liv. 2, 39, and 3, 29. Castris hostium recep- tis.-Caesar de B. Gall. Labienus civitatem recepit-See the learned Mr. Prendeville, on Liv. 2, 39. Scioppius, in his verisimilia, lib. 3r c. 4, produces Virgil AEn. 10, v. 676, already adduced by Broukhusius; as also Juvenal and Propertius, lib. 1, Eleg. 4, v. 27, Praecipere nos· tri. Maneat sic semper, adoro. Adesse for esse in Lucretius, lib. 6, not far from the beginning. Delibata Deum per te tibi numina sancta saepe aderunt. Adstare for stare, in the Carmina Priapeia. Auctum- nis sterilis duobus ads-tans. Adcredere for credere.-Corn. Nepos, in the life of Datames, not far from the beginning. Quem quum omnes prospicerent propter novitatem ornatus, ob eamque rem magnus esset concursus, fuit nonnemo qui agnosceret Thyum, regique nunciaret. Primo non accredit, (sor thus he reads the passage,)——see his Verisi- mil. lib. 3, c. 12. Aderit for erit in Propertius, lib. l, Eleg. 14, v. 23, Quae mihi dum placata aderit ; and lib. 1, Eleg. 2, v. 21, Aderat sor erat. Sed facies aderat nullis obnoxia gemmis. And lib. 2, Eleg. 10, v. 57, Revocare for vocare. Sed frustra mutos revocabis Cynthia manes. Retinere for tenere, in Catullus. Diva, quibus retinens in summis urbibus arces, Accredere for credere in Lucretius, lib. 3, Facile hoc adcredere possis, and in Plautus very frequently. In a similar manner, a person that had never been a member of parliament, is said to be returned, which is a compound verb used for a simple.
